node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

node.title: An Architect’s Matte Black L.A. Home Opens Wide to the Great Outdoors

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dwell on August 20, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
In Barcelona, the bajos—or ground floor—of an apartment building has always had a bad rap. Lack of natural light and dampness are issues, but the opportunity to have a garden in the busy city is enticing. @scala_studio, a young interior design firm founded by Anna Raventós and Lea Viscasillas, was given the opportunity to transform an abandoned office building’s bajos into a father and daughter’s home in Barcelona’s St. Gervasi district. "A haven of peace in the midst of the city’s bustle," is how the designers describe the result. The owner of the space has strong connections to the island of Ibiza and the Costa Brava, and wished to translate a northern Mediterranean feel to the decor where light meets natural warmth and informality. To accommodate this, the designers restored the original woodwork and moldings—such as the arches that lead to the rear garden, and the fireplace. These period details acted as a driver of the original design and decor scheme, which was governed by selecting pieces with a certain romanticism and story to tell. Even the flooring, which was sourced from a 1960s Croatian sawmill, is living a second life in the renovated home. Another impressive feat in reuse comes in the form of a two bedroom unit in the former shed out back. Inside the detached structure, two bedrooms sit on either side of the main bathroom with a walk-in shower. Polished concrete floors and natural wood create a neutral yet cozy ambiance in the shade of a giant ash tree. Behind a dense wall of Passionfruit vines stand twin houses just outside Brisbane, Australia. To mediate the noise and dust from a nearby road, architect John Ellway (@jellway) applied a mesh facade to the dwellings, now covered after only six months. Because the homes are situated on a slope, steel stilts raise the living areas above road level, creating an undercroft surrounded by lush planting. Despite the conscious decisions made to distance the homes from pollutants, Ellway intended for the homes to cultivate community with their surroundings. “In a lot of suburban housing, people drive into a garage, shut the automatic door, and never step outside their sealed box,” he says. “Not in these houses. The entry path is elongated from the footpath to almost halfway up the block, entering a courtyard in the center of the house. It makes a smaller parcel of land feel bigger, but also gives opportunity for casual interactions with the neighbors and provides passive surveillance over each other’s property.” In fact, nearly the entire design focuses on the idea of shared space, not only with the residents of the adjoining house, but also within: The more public spaces in the homes—living, dining, and courtyard—were prioritized in terms of size and detailing, while the bedrooms have a much smaller footprint. This encourages family members to spend time together in the common areas. Designing two homes with community in mind is also a very successful business strategy, allowing for reduced deliveries, use of prefabricated framing, and simple materials such as fiber cement, plasterboard, and aluminum framed windows. In the end, the two lushly landscaped homes came in at around $2,250 AUD per square meter ($153 USD per square foot). Take the full tour of the lush Twin Houses at the link in bio.

On a steep escarpment in Los Angeles, an architect got to build his version of the quintessentially L.A. home. “Many of Los Angeles’ iconic modern houses float above the city like tethered spaceships on stilts,” says @clivewilkinson. “I had always yearned for the opportunity to design my own floating house.” Wilkinson organized the 3,700-square-foot house around a staircase accessed directly from the entry. As soon as you swing open the large pivot door that serves as the front gate, you’re hit with the view, and upstairs, the open living, dining, and kitchen area is oriented toward it. But in the comparatively compact family room and bedrooms, the house manages to revel in the simplicity and domesticity of nearby flatland residences—think bungalows and Spanish-Colonial revival homes—that are standard fare for the region. “I put a lot into this,” says Clive. What he’s gotten out has already proven a hit, as much with family and friends as with its creator. Take a look through the awe-inspiring Wilkinson Residence at the link in bio.

Facing a steep site, poor ground quality, and strong, year-round winds, Pablo Dikenstein of @estudiodikenstein_arquitectos had quite the challenge when designing a beach home in Matanzas, Chile, 300 feet above sea level. The space “provides an astonishing view of the Pacific Ocean,” he says. “Amid the hostile yet charming setting, the structure simultaneously calls upon us to connect and reflect on the best way to inhabit this coastal area.” To temper battering gales and camouflage the home in the landscape, the architect crafted a wooden, honeycomb-like facade that appears suspended in air above exposed concrete retaining walls. A 131-foot-long red ribbon connects the two levels and flows down the hillside, an addition that “allows both structures to benefit from a sea view, and creates a visually pleasing break,” explains Dikenstein. “Casa Panal offers a radical experience and an experimental way of living as it integrates all spaces, both outside and inside, vertical and horizontal.” Take a walk through the entire residence at the link in bio.

For the first time ever, Italian futurist Giacomo Balla’s former apartment in Rome will be open for public viewing. The exhibition, hosted by the city’s National Museum of 21st Century Art (@museomaxxi), grants visitors access to the artist’s otherwise upper-middle class flat that he, his wife, and his two daughters began transforming in 1929 as an inhabitable canvas of art—painting the walls, designing and building furniture, and creating their own imaginative floor tiles, carpets, upholstery, light fixtures, and dishes. The approach to domestication was odd, to be sure, but Balla walked the walk: His 1915 manifesto, penned in partnership with fellow countryman and painter Fortunado Depero, introduced the concept that living life itself should be a “total work of art.” For more on Casa Balla and the exhibition that celebrates the 150th anniversary of the artist's birth, head to the link in bio.

For a young family of five—with a new poodle puppy in tow—this revamped timber cottage in Sydney celebrates lively design. “It’s a humble home with little tweaks that make for playfulness,” says Rebekah Clayton, co-principal of local architecture firm @claytonorszaczky. The goal of the reno was to embrace all that made the weatherboard house special while maxing out the floor plan to better suit the family. To start, the interior walls were blown out to make way for an open-plan kitchen and living area, as well as three bedrooms, bathrooms, and a study. The architects also constructed a cantilevered rear addition that sits atop the original structure—with an eye-catching twist. “For each of our projects, we like to have a gizmo—something fun that’s a bit unexpected or that makes the [structure] unique,” explains Clayton. The showstopper in this case is the fixed screen that wraps the building with white aluminum slats, offering high-visual but low-maintenance impact. Behind the screen, oversize glass doors open up to let in fresh breezes without sacrificing shade or privacy. Despite its striking addition and renovation, the Workers House blends in seamlessly with the rest of the neighborhood from the street. Clayton sums it up: “In some ways this house is the opposite of a standout, and that’s what we consider to be its greatest success.” Take a look through the renovated Workers House at the link in bio.

Dubbed the Michigan Loft for its coveted spot overlooking Michigan Avenue in Chicago’s Motor Row district, this transformed space occupies a century-old building initially used for automotive assembly. Before, its 2,250 square feet felt crowded and disjointed—and altogether too raw. Now, a wood platform wraps the living spaces, creating a more intimate scale. "As one enters this dwelling through a low, wood-clad transition zone, the overwhelming feeling of being inside a large industrial room is very much subdued," says architect @vladimir_radutny. Variations in level allow visitors to experience changing vantage points while moving through more defined areas, from the lofted studio space to the kitchen below. The materials used—like black metal and wood—also create a more cohesive home while maintaining the building’s character. Las Tres Marias—a shared holiday home for three sisters in Spain’s Mont-Roig del Camp—is a striking renovation of a 1960s dwelling that embodies the “courtyard house” character of coastal homes along the Mediterranean. Working in collaboration, architects @bajetgirame and @nicolasburckhardtarchitekten relied on a preexisting wall that lined the property to connect the home to expansive patios. “We sought to create a retreat that is a deliberately ambiguous habitat between the inside and out,” say the architects. While the former layout comprised small, detached spaces, the redesigned 1,292-square-foot residence features living, dining, kitchen, and loggia areas that flow freely under both new and old arches. Renovating this Elysian Heights bungalow was all about adapting, both to the L.A. sun and to the home’s pre-existing structure. @productora_df, a Mexico City–based architecture firm, teamed up with Los Angeles’s @part_office to breathe new life into the previously unremarkable 1930s home that now showcases a striking, bright-blue exterior and sawtooth roof, along with generous windows and doors that open onto shaded patios. While maintaining much of the original structure, the architects also affixed three volumes, creating space for a studio-garage and a primary bedroom. "The project takes advantage of the light across the site," says Wonne Ickx (@wonnex), principal of PRODUCTORA. "You see morning sun through the clerestory windows of the sawtooth extension and sunsets through the new patio windows.” In total, the renovation is a study of contrasts: While the exterior is unified by zingy blue metal cladding, the original volume is rendered in a more subdued stucco. “We really tried for the new addition to establish a dialogue with the previously existing house,” says Ickx. In search of a quiet getaway that could double as a holiday hub for extended family and friends, a Mexico City couple found a three-and-a-half-acre property in Valle de Bravo, a popular weekend destination two hours from the capital. The couple reached out to architects @javiersanchezcorral and @carloscmar who collaborated on a plan for three “floating monoliths” that rise from the landscape. Inspired by Donald Judd’s minimalist works, the three volumes feature board-formed concrete walls with charred wood accents and strategically placed cutouts to frame views of the surrounding terrain. “Weekend estates should push users to experience life differently from the way they do in the city,” says Sánchez. “Splitting the residence into smaller ‘houses’ creates independence for multiple inhabitants, while walking from one volume to the next allows for contemplation and engagement with the landscape, the weather, and the views.” Tour the commanding, concrete trio when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

A dusty-pink facade is only a hint of what’s inside this 18th-century structure. For Sérgio Antunes, cofounder of Lisbon-based @auroraarquitectos, the charming exterior and its rich pigment provided a fascinating starting point for the renovation of the Rose Building—a single-family residence in southern Portugal that he and @furo_architecturestudio turned into five glowing apartments. Throughout are huge swaths of color with unique touches: For example, painted on the ceiling of the central stair is a moody mural of a woman in the style of a fresco, and in one of the unit’s bathrooms, more artwork on the ceiling depicts a mermaid emerging from a swirl of waves. Elsewhere, arched windows, sloped ceilings, ornate moldings, and wooden doors elegantly play off Portuguese marble and patterned ceramic tiles. With the go-ahead from the city, the architects were also able to construct a modern addition at the rear—The Mustard Building—that pairs natural wood partitions with the subdued tones of creamy terrazzo. For more of the dazzling residence-turned-apartment building, head to the link in bio.
